    <h2> Major Events of Addams' Life </h2>
      <div id="tribute-info">
        <h3> Settlement Reform</h3>
          <ul>
            <li> <strong> 1887 -</strong> Addams first reads about the idea of a settlement house </li>
            <li> <strong> 1888 -</strong> Addams travels to London to visit and observe a settlement house </li>
            <li> <strong> 1889 -</strong> Addams opens the Hull House settlement house in Chicago housing 25 women at its peak </li>
            <li> <strong> 1909 -</strong> Addams is elected as the first female president of the National Conference of Charities and Corrections </li>
            <li> <strong> 1914 -</strong> Addams is selected as the first head of the National Federation of Settlement and Neighborhood Centers </li>
          </ul>
        <h3> Civil Rights for Women and Ethnic Minorities </h3>
          <ul>
            <li> <strong> 1903 -</strong> Addams becomes VP of National Women's Trade Union </li>
            <li> <strong> 1909 -</strong> Helps to Found NAACP </li>
            <li> <strong> 1911 -</strong> Addams becomes First VP of National American Woman Suffrage Association </li>
            <li> <strong> 1915 -</strong> Helps organize Woman's Peace Party and is elected 1st Chairman </li>
            <li> <strong> 1919 to 1929 -</strong> Founds and Acts as President for Women's International League for Peace and Freedom </li>
            <li><strong> 1931 -</strong> Addams receives the Nobel Peace Prize for her efforts </li>
          </ul>
      </div>
    <p> Follow this link for more <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jane_Addams#Settlement_houseinformation" id="tribute-link" target="_blank"> information about Jane Addams </a> and her life!
